@prune998 this is a volunteer project, most things are less about hard or not rather someone available or not. then, if that someone available or not knows how to do the work etc.

We just had a lot of work going on in other projects, so things like this which have been the same for 3 or 4 years seem less urgent than finishing larger projects.

It is good to express interest, as usually things without 3 people asking for it don't get prioritized. This is definitely a feature worth doing. If you have hands to try it, it could be a fun way to learn about the tools used. Otherwise, we'll ping back this issue when done. shouldn't be too long. cheers!

Assuming following trace:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/193792/83420981-b2488b80-a427-11ea-8a13-216a7026d99e.png)

So the idea of matching different spans in the same trace would be for example to match this trace by specifying tags `http.method=GET and http.path=/_template/zipkin-autocomplete_template`as these tags appear in different spans on this same trace. Indeed, searching for this returns nothing. 

Paging @adriancole then if this should remain open then or not. It's a bit counterintuitive I guess to want to search this way, but i agree if you have uniquely identifying tags (message ids for example) and a large volume of traces and you want to search for an occurence where message X was handled in the beginning and later on message Y in the same trace, it would be surprising not to find it.

